Title: The Behavior of Bid-Ask Spreads and Volume in Options Markets during the Competition for Listings in 1999 
Abstract:
 In August 1999, U.S. exchanges began to compete directly for order flow in
 many options that had been exclusively listed on another exchange,
 shifting 37% of option volume to multiple-listing status by the end of
 September. Effective and quoted bid-ask spreads decrease significantly
 after multiple listings with spreads generally maintaining their initial
 lower levels 1 year later. These results hold for both time series and
 pooled regressions and are robust. We reject that economies of scale in
 market making cause the decrease in spreads and support the view that
 interexchange competition reduces option transaction costs. Copyright 2003 by the American Finance Association. 
