Title: Model Misspecification and Underdiversification 
Abstract:
 In this paper, we study intertemporal portfolio choice when an investor
 accounts explicitly for model misspecification. We develop a framework
 that allows for ambiguity about not just the joint distribution of returns
 for all stocks in the portfolio, but also for different levels of
 ambiguity for the marginal distribution of returns for "any" subset of
 these stocks. We find that when the overall ambiguity about the joint
 distribution of returns is high, then small differences in ambiguity for
 the marginal return distribution will result in a portfolio that is
 significantly underdiversified relative to the standard mean-variance
 portfolio. Copyright 2003 by the American Finance Association. 
